style.text: **License Monitor**
^[%[Example: Access Denials](5)](center)
Situation

From the _Overview _table on the **Overview** sheet it is evident that there have been a number of access denials in the past seven days and many more in the past 28 days. Has this affected a number of different users, or are there specific users who are being denied access frequently?




To investigate this issue, review the _Users Denied Access_ table on either the **User Detail** sheet or the **Login Access History** sheet. The table lists users who were denied access, when they were last denied, and how many times each user was denied access.

customErrorMessage.calcCond: No access denials are associated with your current selections.

style.text: Take Action

Check the _Login Access Passes per User_ table on the **Login ****Access History** sheet to see if any users are exceeding the 28\-day access threshold \(10\). Those users would be candidates for a dedicated user login pass.

In this case, however, no login pass users have exceeded the threshold in last 28 days.

Because there are no login pass users who should be given user pass access, resolving the problem of login access denials can probably be handled by allocating more tokens to the specific groups whose users are being denied access. License tokens are allocated in the Qlik Management Console.

^[%[Example: Reallocation of Tokens](5)](center)^[%[

User Access: Underutilization

**Scenario 1: Appropriate Allocation**

In this case, the _User Access Sessions per User_ table shows that all the login access users have logged more than 10 sessions in the last 28 days. It requires fewer license tokens to service these users with user access passes than it would be to allocate login access passes to any of them.

When managing user access passes, it is important to monitor the number of passes used in the 28\-day period to find users who are not making sufficient use of passes allocated to them.  This can be accomplished using the _User Access Sessions per User_ table on the User Access History sheet.

**Scenario 2: Underutilization of User Access**

In this case, the U_ser Access Sessions per User_ table is sorted ascending by "Last 28 Days" and shows that a number of users listed at the top of the table have accessed  far fewer times than the threshold for a user access pass.  These users could be added to login pass groups, and their user access passes could be reallocated to high\-frequency users who do not currently have user access passes. Or the license tokens used for the user access passes could be converted to login access passes.

style.text: Login Access: Overutilization

When managing login access passes, it is important to monitor the number of login passes used in the 28\-day period to find users who exceed the threshold \(10 passes\)._#[\(Note: only applicable for Token\-based license.\)](7)_
Sort the _Login Access Passes per User_ table in descending order to see the high\-frequency users at the top of the list. The high\-frequency users can be managed more efficiently by giving them user login access.

**Scenario 1: Appropriate utilization**

In this case, the _Login Access Passes per User_ table shows that all the login access users have used fewer than 10 sessions in the last 28 days. It requires fewer license tokens to service these users than it would be to allocate user access passes to any of them.

**Scenario 2: Overutilization**

In this case, the _Login Access Passes per User_ table shows that several users have accessed well over 10 times in the last 28 days. These users are candidates for dedicated user access passes. The number of login passes freed up by reassigning the high\-frequency users would be the sum of the passes the users used in the last 28 days.

style.text: User Access: Unused Passes

**Scenario: Unused User Access Passes**

Referring to the _Unused User Access Passes_ table on the _User Access History_ page, you can quickly see users who were allocated a user access pass but have not accessed the hub.  These users should be considered candidates to de\-allocate and potentially include in a Login Access Rule.
When managing user access passes, it is also helpful to note which users are not making use of the user access pass allocated to them.

customErrorMessage.calcCond: No unused user access tokens associated with current selections - or no REST connector found during reload.

style.text: Login Access: Rebalancing

When managing login access passes, it is important to monitor the balance of login passes used and remaining across all login access rules.
This is easily done by observing the _Login Access Rule Usage_ chart

**QT Americas: Completely exhausted**

All 2,500 login access passes allocated to the login access rule QT Americas have been used, meaning that users attempting to access apps on the hub through this rule will be denied access.  This scenario is a call to action to allocate more tokens to QT Americas or to adjust other license rules to accommodate these users.

**ABC: Running low**

Login access rule _ABC_, on the other hand, still has passes remaining, but is running low. Consider allocating more tokens to this rule or altering the users who can access the Hub through this rule.
